\f1\fs36 \cf2 AWS Lambda Runtime Languages: Node.js,\
Python, Java, Go, and .NET (C#)\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs18 \cf2 AWS Lambda supports many runtimes, but Node.js and Python dominate usage, together accounting\
for well over half of all function invocations . This reflects their mature tooling, ease of use, and large\
communities. Java is a distant third (often legacy migrations), followed by Go (increasingly popular) and\
.NET (C#). Each language offers trade\uc0\u8209 offs in ease of development, operations, and performance. We\
compare them below for a simple CRUD-based serverless API scenario.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs12 \cf3 1\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs27 \cf2 Developer Experience\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs18 \cf2 Node.js and Python are by far the most common Lambda languages (over 50% of invocations) 
\fs12 \cf3 1\

\fs18 \cf2 . Both have\
rich ecosystems, official AWS support, and many examples/tutorials. Common development tools like\
the AWS Serverless Application Model (SAM) and AWS CDK support JavaScript/TypeScript and Python\
out of the box, and AWS provides templates (e.g. TypeScript templates) to scaffold projects. In practice,\
many developers find Node.js slightly more convenient for Lambda: modern bundlers (esbuild,\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs12 \cf3 2\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs18 \cf2 webpack) can tree\uc0\u8209 shake dependencies for smaller packages , npm / yarn workspaces simplify\
monorepo management, and the new AWS SDK for JavaScript (v3) offers a modular, fully Typed API\
(though its command/send style can be verbose) 
\fs12 \cf3 3\

\fs18 \cf2 . In one analysis, Node.js edged out Python in\
overall developer\uc0\u8209 experience (38 vs 35 points) 
\fs12 \cf3 4\

\fs18 \cf2 . Python is nearly as popular due to its simplicity and\
concise syntax, and it benefits from tools like virtualenv/Poetry and AWS Chalice. Developers appreciate\
Python\'92s readability, but they note that packaging can be trickier (no bundler to trim unused code\
means large dependencies like boto3 may inflate package size) 
\fs12 \cf3 2\

\fs18 \cf2 . Also, the AWS SDK for Python\
(boto3) is synchronous only, which can complicate async code and earned Python a slightly lower score\
for SDK experience 
\fs12 \cf3 3\

\fs18 \cf2 . Overall, both Node.js and Python enjoy broad support (IDE plugins, linters like\
ESLint/Flake8, formatters like Prettier/Black) and rapid iteration with AWS Toolkit/SAM, making them\
excellent choices for Lambda development.\
\'95\
\'95\
\'95\
\'95\
Node.js: Strengths \'96 huge ecosystem, excellent monorepo and bundling support, fast startup,\
strong TypeScript support. Weaknesses \'96 managing node_modules bloat, callback/Promise\
complexity, single-threaded nature. High DX: Node often rates top for ease of writing/deploying\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs12 \cf3 5\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

\fs18 \cf2 Lambdas .\
Python: Strengths \'96 very concise code, extensive libraries (especially for data/ML), built-in AWS\
SDK. Weaknesses \'96 larger deployment packages (no tree\uc0\u8209 shaking) 
\fs12 \cf3 2\

\fs18 \cf2 , lack of native async AWS\
SDK (boto3), and modest IDE toolsets (though improving). DX is strong (lots of Lambda\
examples), but slightly edged out by Node in packaging and dependency management.\
Java: Strengths \'96 robust enterprise tooling (IDE support, Maven/Gradle, Spring), static typing,\
mature AWS SDK (v2/v3) with async and sync clients , and clear concurrency constructs (e.g.\
CompletableFuture ) that developers find elegant 
\fs12 \cf3 7\

\fs18 \cf2 . Packaging is straightforward (build a\
fat JAR via Maven) 
\fs12 \cf3 8\

\fs18 \cf2 . Weaknesses \'96 verbose code and boilerplate, longer build/test cycles.\
AWS IntelliJ/VS Code plugins help, but the initial setup (especially managing Java projects) is\
heavier than scripting languages.\
Go: Strengths \'96 simple syntax and tooling (fast compiler, single-binary deployment), good\
concurrency model (goroutines), native AWS SDK v2, and very fast cold starts. Built-in code\
formatting and linting ease style consistency. Weaknesses \'96 smaller standard library/community\
(fewer high-level frameworks), manual dependency setup (Go modules, no built-in project\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab20\partightenfactor0

